Abstract: We use an infinitely repeated prisoner&apos;s dilemma model to examine the role of inter-partner credible threat in international joint ventures (IJVs). Inter-partner credible threat refers to the certainty of either partner&apos;s retaliation given the other partner&apos;s earlier cheating. We argue that inter-partner credible threat represents the first order determinant and partners&apos; management control represents the second order determinant of partner payoffs. When inter-partner credible threat is present, both partners achieve balanced payoffs whereas when it is absent, partners&apos; relative control will determine their relative payoffs. In-depth interview data from four IJVs in China provide preliminary support for our theoretical arguments.&copy; 2002 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (2002) 33, 457&ndash;478
